LoRaWAN didn’t miss the opportunity. The market did.

Every time I hear about LoRaWAN, the conversation is stuck in 2015. We’re still talking about range and multi-year battery life like they're the only things that matter. And look, on paper, it’s all true. The technology works; you can throw a gateway on a roof, scatter sensors across a campus, and you’ll get data. But if you look at where the high-stakes system integration actually happens—buildings, energy plants, industrial control—LoRaWAN is barely a footnote. It’s not because the radio is bad, it’s because the industry stopped at the connectivity layer and called it a finished solution.
The real problem is that LoRaWAN standardizes the transport but completely ignores the meaning. We’ve spent a decade obsessing over how to move bytes through the air, yet we never bothered to agree on what those bytes are supposed to represent. It shows the moment you try to do a real deployment. You buy a sensor from Vendor A and a valve from Vendor B, and while they’re both "LoRaWAN compatible," that compatibility ends the second the payload hits your server. Suddenly you’re staring at a binary blob that requires a custom decoder, manual mapping, and a lot of guesswork. Temperature isn't just temperature; it’s a specific sequence of bits that Vendor A decided on a whim, involving custom offsets and scaling that you only find out about after digging through a 40-page PDF. 
Instead of building a system, you spend your life writing glue code. You aren't an architect anymore; you're just a translator for a dozen different dialects that shouldn't exist in the first place. Compare that to BACnet or SunSpec, or even Zigbee. For all their flaws, those ecosystems at least try to define what a device is. When you see a temperature object there, you know what to expect. With LoRaWAN, you get a "good luck" and a permanent integration tax. Every new device adds more decoding and more fragile assumptions, meaning you never actually integrate "LoRaWAN"—you just integrate one specific, brittle implementation after another.
Then there’s the control issue. People keep trying to force LoRaWAN into active control loops—valves, actuators, real-time adjustments—when it’s fundamentally an asymmetric, sensing-first protocol. Between duty cycle limits and unpredictable downlink latency, you’re basically trying to drive a car by sending it instructions via the postal service. It might work eventually, but you can't build a reliable system on it.
LoRaWAN could have been the default field layer for almost everything. In retrofit environments especially, the physics give it a massive advantage. But it never moved beyond basic connectivity because nobody owned the data layer. Until there’s a canonical model—a way to ensure a sensor looks the same to a BMS regardless of who built it—every integration will remain a custom, expensive headache. It’s a very efficient way to move data, but right now, it’s a miserable way to build a system.